{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prove that the composition of two monomorphisms is a monomorphism. Deduce that one can define a subcategory \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i m}{\i o}{\i n}{\i o}} of a category \u55349?\u56478? by taking the same objects as in \u55349?\u56478?, and defining {\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i m}{\i o}{\i n}{\i o}}}({\i A},\u8198?{\i B}) to be the subset of {\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i A},\u8198?{\i B}) consisting of monomorphisms, for all objects {\i A}, {\i B}. (Cf. Exercise 3.8; of course, in general \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i m}{\i o}{\i n}{\i o}} is not full in \u55349?\u56478?.) Do the same for epimorphisms. Can you define a subcategory \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i n}{\i o}{\i n}{\i m}{\i o}{\i n}{\i o}} of \u55349?\u56478? by restricting to morphisms that are not monomorphisms?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 4.4.a)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Mono\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let be {\i f}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i A},\u8198?{\i B}) and {\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i B},\u8198?{\i C}) be monomorphisms. Let us show that {\i g}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f} is also a monomorphism.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i Z} be an arbitrary object of \u55349?\u56478?, and $\\alpha', \\alpha" \\in Hom_\{\\mathcal\{A\}\} (Z, A)$:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{aligned\}
    (g \\circ f) \\circ \\alpha' = (g \\circ f) \\circ \\alpha''
        & = g \\circ (f \\circ \\alpha') = g \\circ (f \\circ \\alpha'') \\\\
        & \\Rightarrow f \\circ \\alpha' = f \\circ \\alpha'' \\text\{ because $g$ is mono\} \\\\
        & \\Rightarrow         \\alpha' =         \\alpha'' \\text\{ because $f$ is mono\}
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This means that the composition of 2 monomorphisms is always an monomorphism. We can thus make a subcategory. Taking all objects, properties, and homsets of \u55349?\u56478?, but restricting the homsets only to the monomorphisms, we know that this makes a new category \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i m}{\i o}{\i n}{\i o}} since it is closed under composition, has identities (which are iso, and {\i a fortiori} mono) and associativity.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 4.4.b)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Epi\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let be {\i f}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i A},\u8198?{\i B}) and {\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56478?}({\i B},\u8198?{\i C}) be epimorphisms. Let us show that {\i g}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f} is also a epimorphism.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i Z} be an arbitrary object of \u55349?\u56478?, and $\\beta', \\beta" \\in Hom_\{\\mathcal\{C\}\} (C, Z)$:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\begin\{aligned\}
    \\beta' \\circ (g \\circ f) = \\beta'' \\circ (g \\circ f)
        & = (\\beta' \\circ g) \\circ f = (\\beta'' \\circ g) \\circ f \\\\
        & \\Rightarrow \\beta' \\circ g =  \\beta'' \\circ g \\text\{ because $f$ is epi\} \\\\
        & \\Rightarrow \\beta'         =  \\beta''         \\text\{ because $g$ is epi\}
\\end\{aligned\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This means that the composition of 2 epimorphisms is always an epimorphism. We can thus make a subcategory. Taking all objects, properties, and homsets of \u55349?\u56478?, but restricting the homsets only to the epimorphisms, we know that this makes a new category \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i e}{\i p}{\i i}} since it is closed under composition, has identities (which are iso, and {\i a fortiori} epi) and associativity.\par}
