{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We now define the fibered coproduct (or "pushout"). We suggest the reader goes to check section 3.11.4 of this exercises solutions document for a refresher on the "fibered bicoslice category" {\i C}{\super {\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i \u946?}}. We will use the same notation, i.e., fixing two morphisms {\i \u945?}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i C}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A} and {\i \u946?}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i C}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B} (with common domain) in a category \u55349?\u56478?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This means, for any generic object ({\i f},\u8198?{\i g},\u8198?{\i Z}) of {\i C}{\super {\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i \u946?}}, we have the following diagram:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We first propose a candidate for what it means to be a "fibered coproduct", which we will be able to show is an initial object in {\i C}{\super {\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i \u946?}}. A fibered coproduct {\i P} of {\i A} and {\i B} over {\i C} in a category \u55349?\u56478? is an object {\i P} together with morphisms {\i p}{\sub {\i A}}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i P} and {\i p}{\sub {\i B}}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i B}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i P} such that for any object {\i Z} in \u55349?\u56478? and morphisms {\i f}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z} and {\i g}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i B}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z} such that {\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i \u945?}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i \u946?}, there exists a unique morphism {\i h}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i P}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z} such that the following diagram commutes:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We will now show that this object {\i P} induces an initial object in {\i C}{\super {\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i \u946?}}; this boils down to showing that ({\i i}{\sub {\i A}},\u8198?{\i i}{\sub {\i B}},\u8198?{\i P}) is initial in {\i C}{\super {\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i \u946?}}. Let ({\i f},\u8198?{\i g},\u8198?{\i Z}) be an arbitrary object of {\i C}{\super {\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i \u946?}}. A morphism {\i \u963?} from ({\i i}{\sub {\i A}},\u8198?{\i i}{\sub {\i B}},\u8198?{\i P}) to ({\i f},\u8198?{\i g},\u8198?{\i Z}) is a "raising" of a morphism {\i h}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i P}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z} such that {\i h}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i i}{\sub {\i A}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f} and {\i h}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i i}{\sub {\i B}}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}. This lowering {\i \u963?} is unique if and only if {\i h} is unique. Since {\i P} is presupposed to verify the universal property, such an {\i h}, if it exists, is indeed unique. Therefore, ({\i i}{\sub {\i A}},\u8198?{\i i}{\sub {\i B}},\u8198?{\i P}) is initial ({\i a fortiori} terminal) in {\i C}{\super {\i \u945?},\u8198?{\i \u946?}}.\par}
