{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 On injections and surjections\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Injections\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Injections (which aren\u8217't also surjections) have multiple left-inverses (post-inverses). Eg:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i A}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i a},\u8198?{\i b}\} {\i B}\u8196?=\u8196?\{1,\u8198?2,\u8198?3\} {\i f}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B}\u8196?=\u8196?\{({\i a},\u8198?2),\u8198?({\i b},\u8198?3)\}, injective\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i B}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?=\u8196?\{(1,\u8198?{\i a}),\u8198?(2,\u8198?{\i a}),\u8198?(3,\u8198?{\i b})\} {\i g}{\sub 2}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i B}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?=\u8196?\{(1,\u8198?{\i b}),\u8198?(2,\u8198?{\i a}),\u8198?(3,\u8198?{\i b})\}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i g}{\sub 1}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\sub 2}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It is precisely the free element with no antecedent in {\i B} (here, 1) which leaves room for multiple choices, but doesn\u8217't affect the overall inversion process.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Surjections\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Surjections (which aren\u8217't also injections) have multiple right-inverses (pre-inverses), called sections.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i B}\u8196?=\u8196?\{1,\u8198?2,\u8198?3\} {\i A}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i a},\u8198?{\i b}\} {\i f}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i B}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?=\u8196?\{(1,\u8198?{\i a}),\u8198?(2,\u8198?{\i a}),\u8198?(3,\u8198?{\i b})\}, surjective\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B}\u8196?=\u8196?\{({\i a},\u8198?1),\u8198?({\i b},\u8198?3)\} {\i g}{\sub 2}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B}\u8196?=\u8196?\{({\i a},\u8198?2),\u8198?({\i b},\u8198?3)\}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}{\sub 2}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It is precisely the fact that there are multiple elements that map to the same element (here, 1 and 2 to {\i a}) which leaves room for multiple choices, but doesn\u8217't affect the overall inversion process.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Cancellations\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Function Cancellation Lemma: If a composition of functions cancels out, then the first of the pair is an injection, and the second of the pair is a surjection. Algebraically: $$\\forall A, B \\in Obj(\\textbf\{Set\}),
f \\in (A \\to B), g \\in (B \\to A), \\;
    g \\circ f = id_A
\\Rightarrow
    \\begin\{cases\}
        f \\text\{ is injective\} \\\\
        g \\text\{ is surjective\}
    \\end\{cases\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Corollary 1: any post-inverse of an injection is a surjection.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Corollary 2: any pre-inverse of a surjection is an injection.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Proof: Let be {\i A},\u8198?{\i B}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i O}{\i b}{\i j}({\b Set}),\u8198?{\i f}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B}),\u8198?{\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i B}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}),\u8197?{\i g}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 a) Suppose {\i f} is not an injection. This means: \u8707?{\i x},\u8198?{\i y}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i B},\u8197?{\i x}\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?{\i y} and {\i g}({\i x})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}({\i y}) However, with such an {\i f}, we have: {\i g}({\i x})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}({\i y})\u8196?\u8658?\u8196?{\i f}({\i g}({\i x}))\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}({\i g}({\i y}))\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}}({\i x})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}}({\i y})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i x}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i y} This means that {\i f} is an injection. Contradiction.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Conclusion: in this context, {\i f} must be an injection.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 b) Suppose {\i g} is not a surjection. This means: \u8707?{\i a}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i A},\u8197?{\i a}\u8196?\u8713?\u8196?{\i g}({\i B}) Since {\i g}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}}, that means that {\i g}({\i f}({\i a}))\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}}({\i a})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i a}, this means that {\i a}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i g}({\i B}). Contradiction.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Conclusion: in this context, {\i g} must be a surjection.\par}
