{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 On the morphisms of slice and coslice categories\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Given a base category \u55349?\u56478?, and some set {\i A} we wish to study the homsets of the slice (resp. coslice) category \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i A}} (resp. \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i A}}. {\b These homsets might be empty, or have more than one element.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We remind that slice categories consider {\i morphisms to A} as their {\i objects} (written as ({\i Z},\u8198?{\i \u966?}) for any {\i \u966?}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i Z}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}), while coslice categories consider {\i morphisms from A} as their {\i objects} (written as ({\i \u966?},\u8198?{\i Z}) for any {\i \u966?}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}. {\i Morphisms}, of the form {\i \u963?}{\sub {\i A}}\u8196?:\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 1},\u8198?{\i \u966?}{\sub 1})\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 2},\u8198?{\i \u966?}{\sub 2}) (resp. {\i \u963?}{\super {\i A}}\u8196?:\u8196?({\i \u966?}{\sub 1},\u8198?{\i Z}{\sub 1})\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?({\i \u966?}{\sub 2},\u8198?{\i Z}{\sub 2})) in a slice category \u55349?\u56478?{\sub {\i A}} (resp. coslice category \u55349?\u56478?{\super {\i A}}) map such objects to one another if and only if there exists a morphism in \u55349?\u56478? (the base category!) such that {\i \u966?}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u966?}{\sub 2}{\i \u963?} (resp. {\i \u963?}{\i \u966?}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u966?}{\sub 2}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Example of no {\i \u963?} for a slice category\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For example, note that there exist pairs of morphisms {\i f}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}) and {\i f}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}) between which there is no morphism that exists in the slice category. One such example we can make is in ({\i V}{\i e}{\i c}{\i t}{\sub \u8477?}){\sub \u8477?{\super 2}}. If we take the maps:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$f_1 = \\begin\{bmatrix\} 1 & 0 \\\\ 0 & 0 \\end\{bmatrix\} \\in \\mathcal\{L\}(\\mathbb\{R\}^2)$$ $$f_2 = \\begin\{bmatrix\} 0 & 0 \\\\ 0 & 1 \\end\{bmatrix\} \\in \\mathcal\{L\}(\\mathbb\{R\}^2)$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There exists no map {\i \u963?} such that the following diagram commutes (since the output of {\i f}{\sub 1} will always be null in its second coordinate, and the output of {\i f}{\sub 2} will always be null in the first):\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Example of no {\i \u963?} for a coslice category\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 TODO add potato diagram\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Take {\i A}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 2}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i a},\u8198?{\i b},\u8198?{\i c}\}, {\i \u966?}{\sub 2}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}}, and {\i Z}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?\{1,\u8198?2\}. Since |{\i Z}{\sub 1}|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i d}{\i o}{\i m}({\i \u963?})|\u8196?<\u8196?|{\i c}{\i o}{\i d}({\i \u963?})|\u8196?=\u8196?|{\i Z}{\sub 2}|, there is no possible case in which Im({\i \u963?})\u8196?=\u8196?Im({\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}}) (even if {\i \u966?}{\sub 1} is epi).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Example of multiple {\i \u963?}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 TODO add potato diagram\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Another example, this time in a coslice category, with {\i A}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i a},\u8198?{\i b},\u8198?{\i c}\}, we take $\\text\{\\textbf\{Set\}\}_A$. We take {\i Z}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?\{1,\u8198?2,\u8198?3\}, {\i Z}{\sub 2}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i T},\u8198?{\i F}\}. For {\i \u966?}{\sub 1}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?\{({\i a},\u8198?1),\u8198?({\i b},\u8198?1),\u8198?({\i c},\u8198?3)\} and {\i \u966?}{\sub 2}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 2}\u8196?=\u8196?\{({\i a},\u8198?{\i T}),\u8198?({\i b},\u8198?{\i T}),\u8198?({\i c},\u8198?{\i F})\} there exists two elements in {\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56494?\u8495?\u55349?\u56521?{\super {\i A}}}({\i Z}{\sub 1},\u8198?{\i Z}{\sub 2}). These originate from two functions in {\b Set}: {\i \u963?}{\sub {\i \u945?}}\u8196?=\u8196?\{(1,\u8198?{\i T}),\u8198?(2,\u8198?{\i T}),\u8198?(3,\u8198?{\i F})\} and {\i \u963?}{\sub {\i \u946?}}\u8196?=\u8196?\{(1,\u8198?{\i T}),\u8198?(2,\u8198?{\i F}),\u8198?(3,\u8198?{\i F})\}. The free element in 2\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 1} which is not in Im({\i \u966?}{\sub 1}) offers a degree of freedom.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Explanations on the conditions for {\i \u963?}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the first example, what causes the issue is the fact that the images of {\i f}{\sub 1} and {\i f}{\sub 2} in {\i A} are distinct.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the second example, what causes the issue is the fact that we\u8217've reduced our common domain {\i A} to an insufficient intermediary object {\i Z}{\sub 1}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "element which isn\u8217't mapped to offers a degree of freedom and thus breaks unicity" in the last example should remind you of the notes on surjections. Indeed, when comparing {\i \u963?}{\sub {\i \u945?}} and {\i \u963?}{\sub {\i \u946?}}, we\u8217're in a context which is reminiscent of the definition of an epimorphism.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i \u966?}{\sub 2}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u963?}{\sub {\i \u945?}}{\i \u966?}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u963?}{\sub {\i \u945?}}{\i \u966?}{\sub 1}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We can be assured of being able to cancel {\i \u966?}1 iff {\i \u966?}{\sub 1} is an epimorphism, and thus {\i \u963?}, if it exists, is unique. The proof for slice categories is similar, but given the reverse orders, uses monomorphisms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 More generally:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab a) in a slice category, there will be no {\i \u963?} if Im({\i \u966?}{\sub 1})\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?Im({\i \u966?}{\sub 2}) (proof ? and in more general categories than concrete categories ? TODO: iff ?)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab b) in a coslice category, there will be no {\i \u963?} if Pr(Im({\i \u966?}{\sub 1})\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?Pr(Im({\i \u966?}{\sub 2})) (proof ? and in more general categories than concrete categories ? TODO: iff ?)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab c) in a slice category, there is at most a single {\i \u963?} iff {\i \u966?}{\sub 2} is mono\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab d) in a coslice category, there is at most a single {\i \u963?} iff {\i \u966?}{\sub 1} is epi\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (see perhaps https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/over+category and https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/under+category )\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Chapter 1, Section 4\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Notes on counterintuitive rules\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab in some categories (such as \u8484? with \u8804?; or {\b Ring}), "mono and epi" does not imply "iso"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab in every {\i abelian} category, we have that "iso \u8660? epi and mono" (and though {\b Set} is not abelian, the property still holds)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab while in {\b Set}, a function is an epimorphism (surjective) iff it has a pre-inverse, in {\b Grp}, some epimorphisms do not have right inverses.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Chapter 1, Section 5\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Initial and terminal objects\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab there are categories without either initial or terminal objects, such as the preorder category of \u8484? with \u8804?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab there are categories with multiple initial or terminal objects (for example, in {\b Set}, every singleton set is a terminal object); however, these are respectively unique up to isomorphism\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab any object which is both initial and terminal is called a zero object.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Universal properties\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 "Normal" universal properties\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Verbatim: "The most natural context in which to introduce universal properties requires a good familiarity with the language of functors, which we will only introduce at a later stage. [...] We say that a construction satis\u64257?es a universal property (or: \u8217'is the solution to a universal problem\u8217') when it may be viewed as a terminal object of a category."\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Then: "The declaration/explanation of a universal property generally follows the pattern \u8217'object X is universal with respect to the following property: for any Y such that..., there exists a unique morphism Y \u8594? X such that...\u8217'; this explanation hides the de\u64257?nition of an accessory category, and the statement that X is terminal."\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is a complicated way to say: there is some construct to decompose a morphism which is "universal" (always exists) and reduces the rest of the information of the morphism into something "unique" (hence terminal object of some subcategory).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Dual universal properties\par}
